Theſe two adverſaries being now in redineſs, their horſes were brought forth, and they mounted, ready to give battle. The emperor gave ſtrict charge to all his officers of arms, to have a ſpecial eye upon the arch prieſt, leſt he ſhould fly the field, or run away from them. The merchant being mounted, and his ſword girt on him, firſt entered the liſts; then came the arch prieſt, accompanied with nobels of great honor and dignity. The combatants thus entered
VALENTINE AND ORSON. 33entered the liſts, ready to charge each other; king Pepin called out aloud to the merchant, ſaying, My friend, may God give thee victory over this falſe traitor: The merchant replied, Dread king, I doubt not but this might to make this traitorous prieſt confeſs, that he has villanouſly ſought the deſtruction of your ſiſter.—— Then came a herald, and adminiſtered to them both an oath; and after clearing the lifts, left the champions to their fortunes. The marſhals of the field brought each of them a ſpear, which they had no ſooner recieved, but they put ſpurs to their horſes, and ran with ſuch violence together, that their ſpears were broken in their hands: then they ſet forward for another courſe, charging each other with their ſwords, in ſuch a violent manner, that they cut off hwole quarters of the croſſets: the arch prieſt ſeeing himſelf ſo ſtiffly matched, gave over the fight until towards evening, for ſuch was the cuſtom of the country, thinking thereby to weary out the merchant; which the merchant perceiving, he prepared to meet the arch prieſt courageouſly when he encountered him, which being not long after the merchant ſo redoubled his ſtrokes, that he cut off one of his ears;
34 THE HISTORY OFears; and with the violence of the ſame blow, the merchant's ſword fell from his hand; which the arch prieſt ſeeing, put ſpurs to his horſe, and charged him with ſuch violence, that he ran againſt the merchant;s horſe, and thruſt out one of his eyes; the horſe feeling himself hurt, ran up and down as mad, leaping ſo furiouſly that he threw his rider; the merchant's foor hung in the ſtirrup, whereby he was in great danger. King Pepin was ſo diſcouraged at this diſaſter, that the tears trickled down his cheeks.
